  <h1>£26,000 Salary After Tax UK 2025/26</h1>
  <div class="sub">
    Estimated take-home pay for a <b>£26,000 salary</b> in the UK.
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <p class="muted">
      If you earn <b>£26,000 per year</b> in the UK, your estimated take-home pay after income tax and National Insurance is around <b>£21,445 per year</b>, or about <b>£1,787 per month</b>.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      This is a simple estimate for the <b>2025/26 tax year</b> and assumes a standard tax code with no pension deductions, student loan repayments, bonuses, or salary sacrifice arrangements.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="grid3">
      <div class="box">
        <h3>Gross salary</h3>
        <div class="big">£26,000</div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <h3>Estimated annual take-home</h3>
        <div class="big">£21,445</div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <h3>Estimated monthly take-home</h3>
        <div class="big">£1,787</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h2>£26,000 after tax breakdown</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Based on a salary of <b>£26,000</b>, a simple UK estimate would usually include:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><b>Income tax:</b> around £2,686 per year</li>
      <li><b>National Insurance:</b> around £1,869 per year</li>
      <li><b>Total estimated deductions:</b> around £4,555 per year</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted">
      That leaves an estimated net salary of <b>£21,445 per year</b>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h2>£26,000 salary take-home per month</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      A salary of <b>£26,000 a year</b> works out at roughly <b>£1,787 per month</b> after tax, or around <b>£412 per week</b>.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      Your actual pay can be slightly different depending on pension contributions, student loans, overtime, bonuses, and any other deductions through PAYE.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h2>Is £26,000 a good salary in the UK?</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      A <b>£26,000 salary</b> is around the lower-middle range for full-time earnings in many parts of the UK. Your lifestyle on this salary will depend heavily on rent or mortgage costs, travel, childcare, debt, and the cost of living in your area.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      In lower-cost areas, £26,000 can be workable for a single person. In more expensive parts of the country, especially with high housing costs, it can feel much tighter.
    </p>
  </div>

